  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum sentences can increase for more complex cases\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n- Civil monetary penalties\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Enhanced penalties if linked to other criminal activities\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, intent, and whether the offense involves other criminal enterprises.\n\nNote: These are general guidelines based on federal statutes. Actual sentencing can vary depending on specific case circumstances and judicial discretion.",
